IT is not my present purpose to touch upon the assertions os Papists concerning seven degrees or orders of spiritual offices, especially since they are themselves compelled to confess that all below the Deaconate have been added. My only dispute is con- cerning Episcopacy and Presbytery, Nor shall I here subtilly contend, whether Episcopacy be a distinct order from Presbytery, or only another and higher degree in the same order. William of Paris distinctly affirms that Episcopacy is not an order, but an honour,· which is also maintained by Gerson, whose words are these: There is not another power of order in Biskops than in Presbyters, but the same is there in α more perfect mode.
